### Instrument third-party modules with newrelic.instrument()

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/Migration Guide.md

The `newrelic.instrument()` method allows developers to add custom instrumentation to third-party Node.js modules, including those already instrumented by the New Relic agent. This enables more granular monitoring and custom metric collection for specific libraries or functions.

```javascript
/**
 * New method: newrelic.instrument(), newrelic.instrumentDatastore(), etc.
 */
// Example: Instrumenting a custom library function
const myLibrary = require('my-custom-library');

newrelic.instrument('MyCustomLibrary', myLibrary.someMethod, function(err, result) {
  // This callback is executed after myLibrary.someMethod completes.
  // err will contain any error, and result will be the return value.
  console.log('myLibrary.someMethod finished');
});

// Example: Using instrumentDatastore for database operations
const db = require('some-database-driver');

newrelic.instrumentDatastore('MongoDB', db, 'find', {
  // Optional: configuration for datastore instrumentation
});

// Example: Using instrumentWebframework for framework integrations
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

newrelic.instrumentWebframework('Express', app, 'use', {
  // Optional: configuration for web framework instrumentation
});

```

